REQUIRED EDITIONS Available in: All Editions supported by Data Cloud. See Data Cloud edition availability. Data Cloud combines two HTML-based passage extraction methods: semantic-based and windows-based passage extraction. Data cloud first uses the semantic-based method, and if some resulting passages are too long, the passages are processed further using the window-based method. This allows Data Cloud to keep control over the length of the chunked passages. Semantic-based Passage Extraction Semantic-based passage extraction uses the semantic meaning inherent in HTML tags to chunk a document into passages. HTML elements such as headings (

), lists (
    ), or even bold text () acting as a subheading, are considered logical boundaries for passages. Consider this text. And consider its HTML equivalent.

    Enable Custom Time Zones

    Time zone support lets you view time-specific data...

    In this example, each heading tag with a tag acts as a subheading, dividing the document into logical, coherent sections. A properly segmented HTML document, with clear sections demarcated by headings, coherent line breaks, and proper usage of block tags better enables the retrieval of coherent chunked passages.     tags, or raw text separated by line breaks, to chunk documents into passages. If a paragraph doesn’t contain HTML, the aggregation is done at the sentence level. Consider this text. And consider its HTML equivalent.

    Since there is no semantic indicator with windows-based passage extraction, segmentation is based on the blocks or paragraphs lengths. There is no guarantee that passages are meaningfully grouped. Consider this example.

    Chunking Fields in Search Index Configurations When you create a search index configuration for a DMO, you set a strategy for each object field in the index configuration. Select your chunking strategy based on the content that you’re working with. Consider the fields that provide the most relevant context and semantic meaning, how to break those fields up, and how you expect the retrieved results to be used. For example, chunk the custom text fields of a Knowledge Article DMO using the Passage Extraction strategy to make it easier to return semantically similar results when you search.
